sec.p:
The flyback converter output voltage in CCM operation is given by
\begin{equation*}
V_{\text {out }}=\frac{N_{s}}{N_{p}} \cdot \frac{D}{1-D} \cdot V_{\text {in }}
\end{equation*}

where $V_{\text {in }}$ and $V_{\text {out }}$ are the input and output voltages of the converter, respectively. Furthermore, $D$ represents the duty cycle of the PWM signal from gate drive circuit. Also, $N_{p}$ and $N_{s}$ are the transformer's primary and secondary turns ratio of the flyback converter, respectively. The transformer turns ratio of the flyback converter is then defined as
\begin{equation*}
N=\frac{N_{p}}{N_{s}}
\end{equation*}

In DCM operation, the output voltage depends on the energy transfer per cycle
\begin{equation*}
V_{o u t}=V_{i n} \cdot D \cdot \sqrt{\frac{R \cdot T_{s}}{2 \cdot L_{m}}}
\end{equation*}

The boundary condition between CCM and DCM occurs when the magnetizing current reaches zero at the end of the switching cycle
\begin{equation*}
I_{\text {boundary }}=\frac{V_{i n} \cdot D \cdot T_{s}}{2 L_{m}}
\end{equation*}

Transformer current ripple is then approximated as
\begin{equation*}
\Delta I_{p r i}=\frac{V_{i n} \cdot D}{L_{m} \cdot f_{s}}
\end{equation*}
